{
  "answer": "**No work in the Falsafa corpus pairs both doctrines as described.**\n\nThe Parāśara Smṛti (Chapter 1) states the age-specific \"highest dharma\" (*tapas* in Kṛta, *jñāna* in Tretā, *yajña* in Dvāpara, *dāna* in Kali), but it does not mention Dharma losing its four feet (*pāda*) progressively.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Parāśara Smṛti, Chapter 1, [p-afd7d9](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-afd7d9).\n\nExtensive searches across the corpus (including for \"dharma\" with \"foot/feet/leg/pada/quarter(s)/loses/loss\" and yuga terms like Kṛta/Tretā/Dvāpara/Kali) yielded no matches for Dharma progressively losing a foot/leg/pada in successive ages. This motif appears in texts like the Mahābhārata or Viṣṇu Purāṇa (not in the corpus), but nothing here combines both ideas. The corpus covers 37 works, primarily Smṛtis; not every topic is included.",
